447
00:20:48,630 --> 00:20:50,560
<i> Just to the right of that,</i>
<i> right off the edge,</i>

448
00:20:50,670 --> 00:20:53,570
you have this, maybe six,
seven-foot deep sewage canal.

449
00:20:55,470 --> 00:20:57,870
<i> The waterways are disgusting,</i>

450
00:20:57,970 --> 00:21:01,940
but these are basically outflows
for, you know, for human waste.

451
00:21:02,040 --> 00:21:04,650
<i> On the other side</i>
<i> of that canal there's a wall,</i>

452
00:21:04,750 --> 00:21:07,880
<i> and the wall is probably</i>
<i> eight feet high.</i>

453
00:21:07,980 --> 00:21:11,250
<i> We had to get, you know,</i>
<i> all 50 dudes across this area</i>

454
00:21:11,350 --> 00:21:15,060
<i> to get to where the possible</i>
<i> Taliban stronghold was.</i>

455
00:21:15,160 --> 00:21:16,660
<i> Because of the combination</i>

456
00:21:16,760 --> 00:21:18,760
<i> of the steep embankment</i>
<i> and the very high wall,</i>

457
00:21:18,860 --> 00:21:20,930
it was something that
we couldn't just ladder over.

458
00:21:21,000 --> 00:21:23,160
That's the, the normal way
that we would have preferred

459
00:21:23,270 --> 00:21:25,130
to cross a wall like that.

460
00:21:25,230 --> 00:21:27,100
We found a break in the wall

461
00:21:27,200 --> 00:21:29,100
that we had previously
identified

462
00:21:29,200 --> 00:21:30,840
and thought that could be
a potential crossing point.

463
00:21:30,940 --> 00:21:32,470
<i> As we approached, I said,</i>

464
00:21:32,570 --> 00:21:35,410
"Look, if I was a bomber
living anywhere around here,

465
00:21:35,510 --> 00:21:37,840
this is exactly
where I would place a device.

466
00:21:41,380 --> 00:21:42,620
<i> We took this ladder,</i>

467
00:21:42,720 --> 00:21:45,590
<i> and we laid it</i>
<i> across the canal,</i>

468
00:21:45,690 --> 00:21:50,020
and my partner James
walked across,

469
00:21:50,130 --> 00:21:51,190
then Brian walks across.

470
00:21:53,130 --> 00:21:55,300
<i> Walking on the battlefield</i>
<i> puckers you up.</i>

471
00:21:55,400 --> 00:21:57,930
Walking across
one of these bridging ladders

472
00:21:58,030 --> 00:22:01,000
in a wide-open area,
it's very likely a place

473
00:22:01,100 --> 00:22:03,540
that they might also conduct
an ambush.

474
00:22:03,640 --> 00:22:06,040
There might very well be
somebody's sights

475
00:22:06,140 --> 00:22:07,310
trained on me right now,

476
00:22:07,410 --> 00:22:09,380
and so it becomes
very precarious.

477
00:22:12,250 --> 00:22:14,780
Brian gets over there,
and they do their thing.

478
00:22:14,880 --> 00:22:17,520
They look for tripwires,
kind of check the ground to see

479
00:22:17,620 --> 00:22:19,620
if there is disturbed earth and
see if there's pressure plates

480
00:22:19,720 --> 00:22:21,620
or something
that was recently dug there.

481
00:22:21,720 --> 00:22:23,660
<i>I'm making sure there's nothing</i>

482
00:22:23,760 --> 00:22:25,960
<i> where the water</i>
<i> meets the embankment.</i>

483
00:22:26,060 --> 00:22:28,530
Eventually I think I got down
on my hands and knees,

484
00:22:28,630 --> 00:22:31,370
and I pulled that small handheld
metal detector out of my pocket,

485
00:22:31,470 --> 00:22:33,970
and I gently probed the earth
in front of me to, you know,

486
00:22:34,070 --> 00:22:35,840
to look and see
if I could find anything

487
00:22:35,940 --> 00:22:38,440
because I was so convinced
that there was something there.

488
00:22:38,540 --> 00:22:40,570
There had
to be something there.

489
00:22:44,510 --> 00:22:47,350
We were waiting for them
to give us the okay to cross.

490
00:22:49,450 --> 00:22:51,590
<i> We can't take forever</i>
<i> doing that, you know.</i>

491
00:22:51,690 --> 00:22:53,720
<i> The mission, it has to go on.</i>

492
00:22:53,820 --> 00:22:55,560
<i> The things that we're doing</i>
<i> are time-sensitive.</i>

493
00:22:55,660 --> 00:22:56,820
And as I remember,
you know,

494
00:22:56,930 --> 00:22:59,830
I gave the snipers
the signal,

495
00:22:59,930 --> 00:23:02,560
indicated that we were gonna
move ahead.

496
00:23:02,660 --> 00:23:05,230
<i> I start walking across,</i>

497
00:23:05,330 --> 00:23:07,530
<i> and you're doing all this</i>
<i> in the middle of the night,</i>

498
00:23:07,640 --> 00:23:10,040
<i> and you're doing it</i>
<i> weighed down by, you know,</i>

499
00:23:10,140 --> 00:23:12,040
however heavy your rifle
and machine gun is.

500
00:23:12,140 --> 00:23:14,670
You're doing it with a helmet
with night vision on.

501
00:23:14,780 --> 00:23:17,280
That is very disorienting.

502
00:23:24,890 --> 00:23:27,350
And I slipped.

503
00:23:29,190 --> 00:23:30,090
It's sewage,
It's gross, you know.

504
00:23:30,190 --> 00:23:31,690
And you're soaking wet.

505
00:23:31,790 --> 00:23:33,960
I remember dropping
just about every curse word

506
00:23:34,060 --> 00:23:35,960
in the dictionary,
just furious.

507
00:23:36,060 --> 00:23:37,700
Brian turns around
to come back

508
00:23:37,800 --> 00:23:40,030
and help pull me
out of that creek.

509
00:23:40,140 --> 00:23:44,540
I took maybe one or two steps
towards that river way...

510
00:23:49,080 --> 00:23:51,580
<i> There's just a cloud</i>
<i> of-- of dirt,</i>

511
00:23:51,680 --> 00:23:54,550
which browns out
your night vision,
you can't see a thing.

512
00:23:54,650 --> 00:23:56,480
The blast and the concussion,

513
00:23:56,590 --> 00:23:59,720
it's so, so fast, you know,
you don't know what that was.

514
00:24:25,280 --> 00:24:27,380
<i> We're stopped up at the wall</i>

515
00:24:27,480 --> 00:24:29,920
<i> within the first 10 minutes,</i>
<i>15 minutes of, of the objective</i>

516
00:24:30,020 --> 00:24:32,320
and where everybody
is taking a knee and facing out,

517
00:24:32,420 --> 00:24:36,360
and we're figuring out
how we're going to get
past this obstacle.

518
00:24:38,260 --> 00:24:40,230
And the blast went off.

519
00:24:45,830 --> 00:24:49,940
The plume of smoke went up
easily 60, 70 feet into the air.

520
00:24:50,040 --> 00:24:52,770
To be honest,
my first assessment was

521
00:24:52,880 --> 00:24:56,140
whoever was hit by that,
is probably not alive anymore.

522
00:24:59,580 --> 00:25:02,820
The Improvised Explosive Device
that I thought was there

523
00:25:02,920 --> 00:25:05,890
found me,
or, or I found it.

524
00:25:10,090 --> 00:25:12,390
It was just
the brightest white flash

525
00:25:12,490 --> 00:25:14,730
that I can remember,
and, and it blinding me.

526
00:25:14,830 --> 00:25:17,100
You know, in the movies
people always think,

527
00:25:17,200 --> 00:25:19,470
you hear this click,
and then you have time to think,

528
00:25:19,570 --> 00:25:21,600
what was that?
And then an explosion happens.

529
00:25:21,700 --> 00:25:23,300
This just,
it happened immediately

530
00:25:23,410 --> 00:25:24,910
just as quick
as you flick on the lights,

531
00:25:25,010 --> 00:25:27,610
and to me
it felt like this punch

532
00:25:27,710 --> 00:25:30,240
from some heavyweight boxer
had just landed on my chin,

533
00:25:30,350 --> 00:25:32,680
and it tumbled me
through the air.

534
00:25:34,520 --> 00:25:37,350
I can remember feeling
like my teeth were rattled

535
00:25:37,450 --> 00:25:40,620
from this explosion,
and as I'm laying there,

536
00:25:42,390 --> 00:25:45,360
I still had my earphones on
and I could hear at that point,

537
00:25:45,460 --> 00:25:49,030
"EOD was hit, that EOD is down."
And that's me.

538
00:25:49,130 --> 00:25:51,000
That's what really
brought it home,

539
00:25:51,100 --> 00:25:53,370
to say I was the one that,
that triggered this device.

540
00:25:57,640 --> 00:26:00,140
<i> I had no idea</i>
<i> what had just happened.</i>

541
00:26:00,240 --> 00:26:02,540
<i> I thought maybe</i>
<i> it had something</i>
<i> to do with me falling in</i>

542
00:26:02,640 --> 00:26:04,340
<i> or something because</i>
<i> it all happened at, like,</i>
<i> the exact same moment</i>

543
00:26:04,450 --> 00:26:07,450
Brian was coming back to help
pull me out of that creek.

544
00:26:07,550 --> 00:26:10,850
I started climbing my way
out of the canal.

545
00:26:10,950 --> 00:26:15,490
I got up there,
and Brian was laying on his back

546
00:26:15,590 --> 00:26:19,460
right in front
of this break in the wall.

547
00:26:19,560 --> 00:26:22,030
<i> The wind is knocked out of me,</i>
<i> and I can remember,</i>

548
00:26:22,130 --> 00:26:26,470
all this dust
and dirt that had buried
this IED in the ground,

549
00:26:26,570 --> 00:26:29,470
that was all blown up into me.
And I'm laying there,

550
00:26:29,570 --> 00:26:31,610
and I'm realizing, okay,
there's some good reason

551
00:26:31,710 --> 00:26:34,710
that I can't stand up right now,
and I was in a lot of pain.

552
00:26:37,810 --> 00:26:39,550
<i> I still can't see anything</i>

553
00:26:39,650 --> 00:26:41,350
<i> but just like the outline</i>
<i> of a person</i>

554
00:26:41,450 --> 00:26:44,880
<i> because it's so browned out</i>
<i> with sand and dust.</i>

555
00:26:44,990 --> 00:26:47,350
So I started patting down
his arms and his legs,

556
00:26:47,460 --> 00:26:49,760
and I get to where
his knees are, and it stops.

557
00:26:49,860 --> 00:26:52,390
And that didn't click, again.

558
00:26:52,490 --> 00:26:55,060
I didn't realize what had just
happened, what I was feeling.

559
00:26:55,160 --> 00:26:57,100
And I did it again,
and I looked down to his,

560
00:26:57,200 --> 00:26:58,830
about his knees, and then
I didn't feel anything else,

561
00:26:58,930 --> 00:27:00,730
and I thought,
that's really weird.

562
00:27:00,840 --> 00:27:03,900
And that's when my partner
started screaming for a medic.

563
00:27:04,010 --> 00:27:06,370
As soon as I hear that,
you know, it's just,

564
00:27:06,480 --> 00:27:08,540
I don't know
if it's instinct or what,

565
00:27:08,640 --> 00:27:11,540
like I started booking
straight through towards the,

566
00:27:11,650 --> 00:27:13,780
the bridge point.

567
00:27:13,880 --> 00:27:16,580
The training kicks over.
You go on autopilot almost.

568
00:27:16,690 --> 00:27:18,590
<i> It was awesome to see Cody</i>

569
00:27:18,690 --> 00:27:21,590
immediately react
without regard
for his own safety.

570
00:27:21,690 --> 00:27:23,590
We could be in a minefield,
we don't know,

571
00:27:23,690 --> 00:27:24,790
and he didn't care.

572
00:27:24,890 --> 00:27:26,560
It was his job
to be there,

573
00:27:26,660 --> 00:27:28,530
and that's what Rangers do,
we're there for each other.

574
00:27:28,630 --> 00:27:31,400
And he just deadlined
straight for him.

575
00:27:31,500 --> 00:27:33,230
I didn't really think of,
you know,

576
00:27:33,340 --> 00:27:36,240
there could be more IEDs,
or could be an ambush

577
00:27:36,340 --> 00:27:37,600
or something like that.

578
00:27:37,710 --> 00:27:38,770
I just, you know,
someone yelled "medic."

579
00:27:38,870 --> 00:27:40,640
and that's where I'm gonna go.

580
00:27:40,740 --> 00:27:42,980
Cody comes up there,
and he just starts rattling,

581
00:27:43,080 --> 00:27:44,810
rattling off tasks,
"All right, we gotta
get this done,"

582
00:27:44,910 --> 00:27:47,710
and he's just displaying nothing
but the utmost confidence.

583
00:27:47,820 --> 00:27:51,250
<i>- I still didn't know who it was.</i>
<i>- I mean, I think I saw EOD,</i>

584
00:27:51,350 --> 00:27:54,390
<i> so I knew, like,</i>
<i> That's our EOD guy.</i>
<i> That's Mast.</i>

585
00:27:54,490 --> 00:27:57,060
The first thing I look at,
I see his legs.

586
00:27:57,160 --> 00:27:58,490
I'm like,
that's weird.

587
00:27:58,590 --> 00:27:59,960
What the heck are those
tree branches doing

588
00:28:00,060 --> 00:28:02,100
sticking out of his legs,

589
00:28:02,200 --> 00:28:05,330
like is he laying under,
under like a tree branch
or something?

590
00:28:05,430 --> 00:28:07,630
Like, what's going on here?
And I throw my aid bag down,

591
00:28:07,740 --> 00:28:11,070
and I look like, My God,
those are his femurs.

592
00:28:11,170 --> 00:28:12,270
And I think he
said, like,

593
00:28:12,370 --> 00:28:14,640
"I can't breathe"
or whatnot,

594
00:28:14,740 --> 00:28:18,480
so that alarmed me,
so I threw his body armor off,
didn't find any holes.

595
00:28:20,620 --> 00:28:22,820
<i> You know, my lungs feel</i>
<i> like they are filled with,</i>

596
00:28:22,920 --> 00:28:25,750
you know, chalk or something.
It was making me cough,

597
00:28:25,850 --> 00:28:28,860
and I feel like I'm blinded.
I'm having to wipe all the--

598
00:28:28,960 --> 00:28:31,260
all the dirt
and, and all of this
out of my eyes,

599
00:28:31,360 --> 00:28:33,360
And it was right about
at that time that I really

600
00:28:33,460 --> 00:28:36,460
started to figure out
that I was seriously injured.

601
00:28:36,570 --> 00:28:38,330
I'm, I'm looking
at my left arm,

602
00:28:38,430 --> 00:28:42,840
And my left arm,
all of these fingers,
they were broken,

603
00:28:42,940 --> 00:28:46,540
and they were pointing
in just really crazy directions.

604
00:28:49,110 --> 00:28:50,480
<i> This scenario.</i>

605
00:28:50,550 --> 00:28:52,110
<i> I had been trained on</i>
<i> what to do</i>

606
00:28:52,210 --> 00:28:53,380
in situations like this
a hundred times over,

607
00:28:53,480 --> 00:28:55,450
and I froze.

608
00:28:58,790 --> 00:29:02,820
It took a minute, it was weird,
definitely took a minute,

609
00:29:02,920 --> 00:29:05,690
but finally the medic said,
"Throw a tourniquet on him,"

610
00:29:05,790 --> 00:29:08,290
and that's when everything
clicked.

611
00:29:12,330 --> 00:29:15,300
That's about when I kind of
came out of the haze,

612
00:29:15,400 --> 00:29:17,200
and everything kind of
kicked back on, you know.

613
00:29:17,310 --> 00:29:19,410
I had a little system reboot
and kinda thought,

614
00:29:19,510 --> 00:29:22,210
Okay, I know what to do here.

615
00:29:22,310 --> 00:29:24,740
I put a tourniquet
on one of his legs,

616
00:29:24,850 --> 00:29:27,250
the medics put one on his
other leg and then on his arm.

617
00:29:29,120 --> 00:29:30,480
It's probably
the most painful thing

618
00:29:30,590 --> 00:29:32,720
that I can remember
ever happening.

619
00:29:32,820 --> 00:29:36,060
You know, if the end of my limb
looked something like this,

620
00:29:36,160 --> 00:29:38,660
they were wrenching a tourniquet
down on top of it

621
00:29:38,760 --> 00:29:41,390
to tighten it down
as tight as they possibly could

622
00:29:41,500 --> 00:29:44,060
to make sure I don't hemorrhage
out on the battlefield.

623
00:29:44,170 --> 00:29:48,270
We're lucky that, you know,
the blast cauterized his legs,

624
00:29:48,370 --> 00:29:49,700
and he wasn't bleeding
very much.

625
00:29:49,810 --> 00:29:51,740
And then they start
working on other things,

626
00:29:51,840 --> 00:29:55,280
getting his equipment off,
you know, running fluids on him

627
00:29:55,380 --> 00:29:59,450
and doing their thing,
and at that point
I stepped back.

628
00:30:01,850 --> 00:30:03,880
<i> The platoon sergeant is like,</i>

629
00:30:03,990 --> 00:30:06,350
"Doc, you have two minutes
to get over across the river

630
00:30:06,450 --> 00:30:09,420
before the medevac bird
comes down.

631
00:30:09,520 --> 00:30:11,720
Like, he wasn't even
on the cot at all,

632
00:30:11,830 --> 00:30:14,030
the blanket was,
like, getting set up,

633
00:30:14,130 --> 00:30:15,960
so we had to start,
start booking it.

634
00:30:16,060 --> 00:30:18,570
I remember thinking,
"My gosh," you know,
"this is crazy."

635
00:30:46,660 --> 00:30:49,260
<i> After the blast,</i>
<i> we pulled security,</i>

636
00:30:49,360 --> 00:30:51,460
held on tight.
They continued to work on Brian.

637
00:30:51,570 --> 00:30:54,030
We had, you know,
our medics working on him.

638
00:30:54,140 --> 00:30:56,200
<i> I'm working on the edge</i>
<i> of this riverbank,</i>

639
00:30:56,300 --> 00:30:59,940
so I'm like, partly falling off
and trying not to lose my bag

640
00:31:00,040 --> 00:31:02,440
and my gear and not let him
fall in, you know,

641
00:31:02,540 --> 00:31:04,610
and trying to get him
packaged up, so we're like,

642
00:31:04,710 --> 00:31:07,910
we got two minutes
to get over across the river.

643
00:31:08,020 --> 00:31:11,220
I'm kind of talking to Brian,
trying to get IV access.

644
00:31:11,320 --> 00:31:14,490
I asked him to see if he was,
like, with it or not,
alert and oriented.

645
00:31:14,590 --> 00:31:17,320
So like, "Hey, Mast, can you
tell me your first name?"

646
00:31:17,430 --> 00:31:19,660
He was asking me questions
that they're trained to ask,

647
00:31:19,760 --> 00:31:22,660
you know, things to basically
help keep my mind sharp

648
00:31:22,760 --> 00:31:24,760
and my mind focused
and prevent shock.

649
00:31:24,870 --> 00:31:27,970
And he said that I was almost
offended as though, you know,

650
00:31:28,070 --> 00:31:31,240
What, you don't,
how do you not know my name?

651
00:31:31,340 --> 00:31:32,940
<i> He wasn't screaming</i>
<i> or anything like that,</i>

652
00:31:33,040 --> 00:31:35,810
so it kinda, kinda threw me off
initially, like I mean,

653
00:31:35,910 --> 00:31:38,850
he's lost both your legs,
a big wound on your arm,

654
00:31:38,950 --> 00:31:42,120
just kind of inappropriately
calm, you know?

655
00:31:44,290 --> 00:31:46,620
Before really getting ready
to lift him and move him,

656
00:31:46,720 --> 00:31:49,360
he's like, "Hey, can I have
something for the med--

657
00:31:49,460 --> 00:31:51,990
for the pain?"
I'm like, that hit me like,

658
00:31:52,090 --> 00:31:54,990
Crap, like, how did I
completely forget about this?

659
00:31:55,100 --> 00:31:56,860
I grabbed one of our
fentanyl lollipops,

660
00:31:56,970 --> 00:31:59,330
just kinda like a morphine
derivative.

661
00:31:59,430 --> 00:32:02,200
So then we taped it
to his finger and told him

662
00:32:02,300 --> 00:32:04,040
to put it in his mouth
and just suck on it.

663
00:32:06,710 --> 00:32:09,610
<i> After that, they got</i>
<i> me onto the stretcher,</i>

664
00:32:09,710 --> 00:32:13,150
and this all happened
in a really quick period
of time.

665
00:32:13,250 --> 00:32:14,810
<i>- This canal that</i>
<i>- I was doing everything</i>

666
00:32:14,920 --> 00:32:16,880
<i> I could to not fall into,</i>

667
00:32:16,990 --> 00:32:19,350
we had to have a bunch of guys,
like, dive in there.

668
00:32:19,450 --> 00:32:21,720
We had a four-person carry team,
one on each--

669
00:32:21,820 --> 00:32:23,790
one of the legs
of the stretcher.

670
00:32:23,890 --> 00:32:25,830
We kind of had to ladder down.

671
00:32:25,930 --> 00:32:27,830
<i> Brian is a big dude,</i>

672
00:32:27,930 --> 00:32:29,400
and he's weighed down
by all of his equipment,

673
00:32:29,500 --> 00:32:33,000
and carrying him,
it was tough, you know.

674
00:32:33,100 --> 00:32:35,030
<i> It was a very surreal</i>
<i> experience</i>

675
00:32:35,140 --> 00:32:37,540
<i> being transported</i>
<i> on the stretcher.</i>

676
00:32:37,640 --> 00:32:39,210
We're used to seeing
the world go by

677
00:32:39,310 --> 00:32:41,310
as we walk around the world
vertically,

678
00:32:41,410 --> 00:32:43,780
and all of a sudden I'm laying
on the flat of my back,

679
00:32:43,880 --> 00:32:47,050
and I'm seeing
the world go by like this.

680
00:32:49,250 --> 00:32:52,150
As we get close
to that helicopter,

681
00:32:52,250 --> 00:32:55,050
it kicks up a huge amount
of dust and dirt
and hay and straw

682
00:32:55,160 --> 00:32:56,990
and anything else
that might be on the ground.

683
00:32:57,090 --> 00:32:59,230
I don't have any goggles on,
and so all of that

684
00:32:59,330 --> 00:33:02,060
that the helicopters kick up,
it's all landing on top of me.

685
00:33:02,160 --> 00:33:05,570
And it was just,
it was a very surreal
experience.

686
00:33:05,670 --> 00:33:08,200
You know,
somebody gave me a salute

687
00:33:08,300 --> 00:33:10,800
and told me
that I was gonna be okay.

688
00:33:10,910 --> 00:33:14,040
And that's the last thing
that I remember from that night.

689
00:33:19,150 --> 00:33:20,680
<i> We got him out of that field,</i>

690
00:33:20,780 --> 00:33:24,080
and the helicopters
picked him up and took off,

691
00:33:24,190 --> 00:33:25,950
and it was dead silent.

692
00:33:26,050 --> 00:33:27,650
And we're right back
where we started,

693
00:33:27,760 --> 00:33:30,260
just short one guy.

694
00:33:33,460 --> 00:33:35,560
<i> As soon as that bird</i>
<i> left, I was just exhausted,</i>

695
00:33:35,660 --> 00:33:37,230
<i> like, mentally</i>
<i> and kind of physically, too,</i>

696
00:33:37,330 --> 00:33:39,600
but we had a whole
30-hour mission ahead of us,

697
00:33:39,700 --> 00:33:41,870
so, you know,
you don't really
have time to relax

698
00:33:41,970 --> 00:33:43,640
and just do the next part.

699
00:33:43,740 --> 00:33:46,110
<i> We took a quick</i>
<i> regrouping break</i>

700
00:33:46,210 --> 00:33:48,370
<i> to kind of figure out where</i>
<i> we were gonna go from there.</i>

701
00:33:48,480 --> 00:33:50,440
It was about that time
that we started to realize

702
00:33:50,550 --> 00:33:52,480
that this area
that we're working in right now,

703
00:33:52,580 --> 00:33:55,450
there's nobody here,
and there's all these mines

704
00:33:55,550 --> 00:33:57,450
and explosives everywhere,
and I just kinda thought,

705
00:33:57,550 --> 00:34:00,650
you know, it's like this is like
one giant trap that they set.

706
00:34:00,760 --> 00:34:03,220
You have to fight on
to the Ranger objective.

707
00:34:03,320 --> 00:34:05,290
That's, that's the creed.
That's what we do.

708
00:34:05,390 --> 00:34:07,090
<i> And so we made a decision</i>
<i> to move on</i>

709
00:34:07,200 --> 00:34:11,230
<i> and to continue the mission</i>
<i> and find a new route.</i>

710
00:34:11,330 --> 00:34:13,300
I was terrified.
Terrified.

711
00:34:13,400 --> 00:34:15,330
And, you know,
I'm not ashamed to admit that.

712
00:34:15,440 --> 00:34:17,570
I think there's a lot of people
that won't,

713
00:34:17,670 --> 00:34:19,410
but, you know,
that's how I felt.

714
00:34:21,110 --> 00:34:23,840
<i> We would cross</i>
<i> the river, waist deep,</i>

715
00:34:23,950 --> 00:34:26,310
<i> and cross back</i>
<i> and kinda go back and forth.</i>

716
00:34:26,410 --> 00:34:28,750
I feel like we crossed it, like,
four or five different times,

717
00:34:28,850 --> 00:34:31,150
and it sucks getting wet.

718
00:34:31,250 --> 00:34:33,690
<i> It was a little</i>
<i> nerve-wracking to be walking</i>

719
00:34:33,790 --> 00:34:36,160
in waist deep, and up to
some parts chest-deep water,

720
00:34:36,260 --> 00:34:39,030
and not knowing
the next step.

721
00:34:39,130 --> 00:34:43,130
<i> It took hour, hour and a half,</i>
<i> to get to our objective.</i>

722
00:34:45,070 --> 00:34:47,600
That was an occupied compound,
people lived there,

723
00:34:47,700 --> 00:34:50,500
and we set up shop
just like we always do.

724
00:34:50,610 --> 00:34:52,540
<i> Once we were all</i>
<i> in the compound,</i>

725
00:34:52,640 --> 00:34:54,640
<i> and we had all our positions,</i>
<i> you just kind of sit there</i>

726
00:34:54,740 --> 00:34:57,140
and wait and pull security,
kind of calm down

727
00:34:57,250 --> 00:34:59,050
and let all this
kind of come over you.

728
00:34:59,150 --> 00:35:02,010
That's when I kinda realized
that when this blast went off,

729
00:35:02,120 --> 00:35:05,790
I was in this canal,
and Brian's standing

730
00:35:05,890 --> 00:35:09,960
maybe at four feet offset
from where my head was.

731
00:35:10,060 --> 00:35:11,990
Throughout my entire
military career,

732
00:35:12,090 --> 00:35:14,190
through all the training,
through all the missions prior,

733
00:35:14,300 --> 00:35:16,400
I had had nothing
but the utmost confidence

734
00:35:16,500 --> 00:35:18,900
that I was never frightened
by anything.

735
00:35:19,000 --> 00:35:21,070
I had been in, you know,
numerous firefights.

736
00:35:21,170 --> 00:35:23,200
I always felt, you know,
comfortable in my element,

737
00:35:23,300 --> 00:35:25,840
and this totally
threw me off.

738
00:35:25,940 --> 00:35:27,870
I was terrified.

739
00:35:27,980 --> 00:35:29,810
<i> I thought we were,</i>
<i> like, the best, you know.</i>

740
00:35:29,910 --> 00:35:31,540
<i> No one can touch us.</i>
<i> We're invincible.</i>

741
00:35:31,650 --> 00:35:33,550
<i> It's part of the training,</i>
<i> part of the mentality,</i>

742
00:35:33,650 --> 00:35:36,320
<i> and, you know, once you,</i>
<i> like, have a casualty</i>

743
00:35:36,420 --> 00:35:38,550
or lose one of your own,
it's very humbling.

744
00:35:38,650 --> 00:35:40,820
Going through all this stuff
together

745
00:35:40,920 --> 00:35:43,820
just kind of solidifies
your unity.

746
00:35:43,930 --> 00:35:46,860
Say you have bad moments
here and there, but, you know,

747
00:35:46,960 --> 00:35:48,560
when you're down,
someone else is right there

748
00:35:48,660 --> 00:35:50,700
to pick you up, too,
and you kind of just feed off

749
00:35:50,800 --> 00:35:52,870
each other's strength
and courage.

750
00:35:52,970 --> 00:35:55,840
<i> We were really tired,</i>
<i> and when you deal</i>

751
00:35:55,940 --> 00:35:57,440
<i> with something</i>
<i> like a medevac,</i>

752
00:35:57,540 --> 00:35:59,510
or you see somebody
get injured,

753
00:35:59,610 --> 00:36:01,610
your adrenaline wears down,
and you get a little
more drained.

754
00:36:01,710 --> 00:36:04,840
So mentally
I was a little more drained,
and I was ready to leave.

755
00:36:04,950 --> 00:36:07,950
We had very, very sparse
contact that whole day.

756
00:36:08,050 --> 00:36:09,750
It was a very,
very quiet mission

757
00:36:09,850 --> 00:36:12,450
relative to all the other
missions that we had been on.

758
00:36:12,550 --> 00:36:14,690
<i> I think it was</i>
<i> 10:00 PM local time,</i>

759
00:36:14,790 --> 00:36:17,690
<i> it's when we kind of</i>
<i> make our way to exfil.</i>

760
00:36:17,790 --> 00:36:20,230
Once I got back to base,
not a lot of time

761
00:36:20,330 --> 00:36:22,430
to kind of sit and ponder
"what if's"

762
00:36:22,530 --> 00:36:23,700
or what happened here,

763
00:36:23,800 --> 00:36:25,260
or I wonder
how Brian is doing

764
00:36:25,370 --> 00:36:27,130
because you start planning
for the next mission,

765
00:36:27,240 --> 00:36:29,440
and we gotta go do the same
thing the next day.

766
00:36:44,950 --> 00:36:49,090
The next memory that I have
is about five days later,

767
00:36:49,160 --> 00:36:53,090
when I woke up to this nurse
asking me if I knew where I was,

768
00:36:53,190 --> 00:36:56,560
and, to which I said,
"I have no idea where I am."

769
00:36:56,660 --> 00:36:58,900
And she said, you know,
"Your name is Brian Mast.

770
00:36:59,000 --> 00:37:01,970
You're in Washington DC at
Walter Reed Army Medical Center,

771
00:37:02,070 --> 00:37:04,870
and you're gonna be in surgery
in a couple of hours.

772
00:37:07,810 --> 00:37:09,640
<i> I didn't even know</i>
<i> at that point</i>

773
00:37:09,740 --> 00:37:12,910
<i> really what my injuries were.</i>

774
00:37:13,010 --> 00:37:15,620
I didn't know
that I had just, you know,

775
00:37:15,720 --> 00:37:18,780
had both of my legs amputated
somewhere above my knees,

776
00:37:18,850 --> 00:37:22,290
or that I had
a missing index finger
or damage to my forearm.

777
00:37:22,390 --> 00:37:25,590
I really didn't know
what the injuries were.

778
00:37:27,500 --> 00:37:30,830
I honestly believed, you know,
in those first couple of weeks

779
00:37:30,930 --> 00:37:35,940
after injury that I was gonna
slap on a pair of prosthetics,

780
00:37:36,040 --> 00:37:38,400
do physical therapy
for a couple of weeks,

781
00:37:38,510 --> 00:37:40,940
<i> and I was gonna</i>
<i> be out on the next rotation,</i>

782
00:37:41,040 --> 00:37:42,280
<i> you know,</i>
<i> with those guys,</i>

783
00:37:42,380 --> 00:37:45,140
<i> working on</i>
<i> the battlefield again.</i>

784
00:37:45,250 --> 00:37:49,850
<i> I didn't fully realize</i>
<i> that I was about to enter</i>
<i> a new normal to life</i>

785
00:37:49,950 --> 00:37:52,850
<i> that didn't involve</i>
<i> being on the battlefield,</i>

786
00:37:52,950 --> 00:37:56,320
<i> you know, with these guys</i>
<i> that I call my brothers.</i>

787
00:37:58,630 --> 00:38:02,360
I would no longer
be able to be an asset
to the mission that,

788
00:38:02,460 --> 00:38:05,000
you know, if I ever ended up
on the battlefield again,

789
00:38:05,100 --> 00:38:06,870
I would probably,
in all reality,

790
00:38:06,930 --> 00:38:09,670
be a detriment to the mission,
and I think that's something

791
00:38:09,770 --> 00:38:13,510
that can be very difficult
for a lot, for a lot of guys

792
00:38:13,610 --> 00:38:17,240
to come to grips with,
to some degree.

793
00:38:21,820 --> 00:38:24,180
<i> The way that I perceive</i>
<i> this whole thing,</i>

794
00:38:24,250 --> 00:38:26,220
<i> I think</i>
<i> it's luck of the draw.</i>

795
00:38:26,320 --> 00:38:28,890
You know, you have
50-some people,

796
00:38:28,990 --> 00:38:32,060
so it's inevitable
that somebody is probably
gonna step on that.

797
00:38:33,800 --> 00:38:36,030
But I think it was because
Brian was coming back

798
00:38:36,130 --> 00:38:37,060
to help pull me
out of that creek,

799
00:38:37,170 --> 00:38:42,300
which was a crazy thought,

800
00:38:42,400 --> 00:38:45,470
something I thought
about a lot.

801
00:38:48,410 --> 00:38:51,840
I don't think there's,
for even one second,

802
00:38:51,950 --> 00:38:54,080
that Zach should feel guilty
about anything.

803
00:38:54,150 --> 00:38:57,150
We're on the battlefield,
and we do the best that we can

804
00:38:57,250 --> 00:38:59,690
for each other,
for as long as we can do it,

805
00:38:59,790 --> 00:39:02,360
in the best way that we know it
at that specific second.

806
00:39:02,460 --> 00:39:05,060
So I like to think that,
you know, the last thing

807
00:39:05,160 --> 00:39:06,860
that I ever did
on the battlefield

808
00:39:06,930 --> 00:39:10,000
was to put myself between,
you know, one of those brothers

809
00:39:10,100 --> 00:39:11,930
and possible injury
and possible death.

810
00:39:12,030 --> 00:39:13,770
It was supposed to be me.

811
00:39:13,870 --> 00:39:18,840
It wasn't supposed to be him
or any of the other Rangers.

812
00:39:22,510 --> 00:39:24,440
<i> It wasn't until</i>
<i> after this incident</i>

813
00:39:24,550 --> 00:39:26,350
that I really got to,
you know, see him,

814
00:39:26,450 --> 00:39:28,080
see his personality,

815
00:39:28,180 --> 00:39:30,380
kind of see how he handles
tragedy, how he handles this,

816
00:39:30,450 --> 00:39:32,690
you know, this, this horrible
thing that's happened to him.

817
00:39:32,790 --> 00:39:37,290
Being able to walk
and regain his normal
functioning is just,

818
00:39:37,390 --> 00:39:41,030
you know, it's quite
the testament of, you know,

819
00:39:41,130 --> 00:39:43,200
his strength and his drive.

820
00:39:43,300 --> 00:39:45,600
It's awesome to see
a guy like that

821
00:39:45,700 --> 00:39:48,470
have so much determination,
and he's an inspiration

822
00:39:48,570 --> 00:39:50,500
to other veterans
who have gone through,

823
00:39:50,610 --> 00:39:51,870
you know,
situations like his.

824
00:39:58,680 --> 00:40:00,080
<i> The thing</i>
<i> that I'm most proud of,</i>

825
00:40:00,180 --> 00:40:03,380
it's not any,
any medal or award.

826
00:40:03,480 --> 00:40:05,420
<i> It's when the Rangers</i>
<i> gave me a ceremony</i>

827
00:40:05,520 --> 00:40:09,560
<i> to make me an honorary member</i>
<i> of the 75th Ranger Regiment.</i>

828
00:40:09,660 --> 00:40:11,390
That day they said,

829
00:40:11,490 --> 00:40:15,060
"You're officially a Ranger.
You're officially one of us."

830
00:40:17,060 --> 00:40:20,270
<i> He is a Ranger in my book.</i>

831
00:40:20,370 --> 00:40:22,640
There is no question about that,
and a lot of guys

832
00:40:22,740 --> 00:40:25,570
are just as hard as him
and just as determined as him.

833
00:40:29,010 --> 00:40:30,910
<i> That was part of what</i>
<i> makes me so proud</i>

834
00:40:31,010 --> 00:40:32,610
<i> about these guys</i>
<i> that I work with,</i>

835
00:40:32,710 --> 00:40:35,250
is they are the tip
of the spear.

836
00:40:35,350 --> 00:40:39,520
<i> Going out every single night,</i>
<i> knowing the hazards</i>

837
00:40:39,620 --> 00:40:42,820
<i> that they were going</i>
<i> to have to combat.</i>

838
00:40:42,920 --> 00:40:46,530
Taking contact and losing guys,
it's just kinda,

839
00:40:46,630 --> 00:40:49,200
it's hard to put into words
that kind of experience.

840
00:40:49,300 --> 00:40:53,270
Just very thankful that you
get home alive, in one piece.

841
00:40:53,370 --> 00:40:56,340
I learned more about myself,
and more especially

842
00:40:56,440 --> 00:40:58,040
about the people
that I was working with

843
00:40:58,140 --> 00:41:00,640
on that deployment
than any other.

844
00:41:00,740 --> 00:41:03,440
<i> It was a real learning curve</i>

845
00:41:03,540 --> 00:41:05,180
and involved
life and death.

846
00:41:05,280 --> 00:41:07,150
You couldn't ask for a better
group of guys to be with.

847
00:41:07,250 --> 00:41:09,050
<i> This Merrill deployment</i>
<i> changed the game.</i>

848
00:41:09,150 --> 00:41:11,020
<i> We had lost several guys,</i>
<i> we lost dogs.</i>

849
00:41:11,120 --> 00:41:13,790
We had at least a quarter,
if not a third,

850
00:41:13,890 --> 00:41:16,160
of everybody there
had received a Purple Heart

851
00:41:16,260 --> 00:41:17,890
for getting wounded
in some other fashion,

852
00:41:17,990 --> 00:41:19,230
<i> whether</i>
<i> it was something</i>
<i> on a grand scale</i>

853
00:41:19,330 --> 00:41:20,760
<i> like Brian</i>
<i> losing his legs,</i>

854
00:41:20,860 --> 00:41:23,330
or somebody just catching
a piece of shrapnel.

855
00:41:26,430 --> 00:41:28,970
Americans have always been
willing to pay that price,

856
00:41:29,070 --> 00:41:31,400
and those Rangers
that I work with,

857
00:41:31,510 --> 00:41:34,370
they, they embody
that every single night.

